issue.title: Bitcoin-Qt crashes on OS X

@jarimustonen 

Thanks for report. Could you also provide your `Library/Application Support/Bitcoin/debug.log` file?

Similar to #21402, same crashed thread and exception code.

`Bitcoin-Qt` is not officially supported on M1 hardware yet, you are running a version built for Intel running in emulated mode.  We hope to get to official support soon with #21851. 

You can try one of two things for now: 
1) Try to compile `Bitcoin-Qt` natively through depends.
    - for now this is experimental, and you are likely to run into issues doing so.
2) Follow the steps that worked to resolve the issue for the person who opened #21402

https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/issues/21402#issuecomment-801933139
> Sorry for the late reply.
> I downloaded the whole blockchains data and create a new wallet by Bitcoin Core 0.21 (binary release ,rosseta mode). 
> Then I copy my old wallet.dat to replace the new empty wallet file.All done, running successfully with no crash.
> I don't know what happened before.I will reopen the issue if there is new crash.
> Thank you all for replying my issue, a lot.

@jarimustonen 

Thanks for providing more info.

Your `debug.log` does not contain any signs of wrong behavior in Bitcoin Core code. All your settings and directories are default.

My bet is the combination Bitcoin Core v0.21.1 + Rosetta + Apple M1 is not compatible between each other. And, definitely, it was not well tested by developers.

Maybe, a developer who has an access to Apple M1 hardware could reproduce this issue on his hardware, and define the part which is responsible for a crash.

As an attempt to get it work, you could try to:
- create an empty `/Users/piialiisa/Library/Application Support/Bitcoin/bitcoin.conf` file
- put the only text line `par=1` in it (this will set the number of script verification threads to 1, i.e., no parallelization)
- and run Bitcoin Core again

I tried this also on Inter Mac with same result. I have a wallet that has its first transaction approximately at the time of the crash (Sep 20th 2017). If the wallet is open Bitcoin-Qt crashes but it is able to proceed normally if the wallet is not there.

Is the wallet file such that I can provide it to this bug report without compromising it?

This being related to wallets and transactions reminds me of https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/issues/20776. It could be that [gui #204](https://github.com/bitcoin-core/gui/pull/204) has already fixed this. 

Commit 3913d1e8c1f604bdd622d5e81e5077ef52b30466 is not in the [0.21](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/commits/0.21) or [0.20](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/commits/0.20) branches so it's not in any of the available releases. It will be included in the next Bitcoin Core release.

If you're feeling adventurous, you could compile master following the [build-osx.md](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/master/doc/build-osx.md) and run it with your wallets to see if the issue is resolved. This would be helpful to know if there is still something to investigate here or if it's something which has already been fixed.

BTW next time you have an issue related to the GUI; please open it up here: https://github.com/bitcoin-core/gui

> yes, if i open 0.21.1 without the wallet it loads fine, it's only when the wallet is being rescanned does it crash.
> 
> please try installing 0.20.1 and see if it work with your wallet -- then if it works, install 0.21.1 after (don't delete the wallet) and see if it works ... this fixed the problem for me. 0.21.1 loads fine with the wallet after upgrading from 0.20.1 for some reason.
> 

Ok. I try this. Will take some time as I need to download the whole blockchain again. I'll let you know how it goes.
@jarimustonen did you end up following up here?
@jarimustonen we now have official support for m1 machines, could you please test these binaries out and see if your problems persist. Otherwise, this issue can be closed.
Closing for now. Let us know if this should be reopened.
